## Diagnosis

The Input component's resting border is rendering at 2px when it should be 1px (hairline). The two-axis grammar (color channel + weight channel) is structurally correct but both axis values are misconfigured — the weight channel isn't differentiating between resting and engaged states.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — State conflation on the weight axis.**

The engaged weight (2px) is leaking into the resting state because the base border-width token is set to `2px` and the ring is being painted additively on top rather than the base being a true hairline. The weight axis has only one value instead of two distinct stops.

---

## Fix

### 1. Token definitions — `tokens/border.css`

```css
/* tokens/border.css */
@layer elan.tokens {
  :root {
    /* ── Weight axis ────────────────────────────────────── */
    --border-weight-hairline:  1px;   /* resting  */
    --border-weight-engaged:   2px;   /* focused / active */

    /* ── Color axis ─────────────────────────────────────── */
    --border-color-resting:    var(--color-neutral-300);
    --border-color-engaged:    var(--color-accent-500);
    --border-color-error:      var(--color-error-500);
    --border-color-disabled:   var(--color-neutral-200);
  }
}
```

### 2. Input component styles — `components/Input/Input.css`

```css
/* components/Input/Input.css */
@layer elan.components {

  .input {
    /* Weight axis: hairline at rest — single border, no ring */
    border-width:  var(--border-weight-hairline);   /* 1px */
    border-style:  solid;
    border-color:  var(--border-color-resting);

    /* Ring scaffold: zero-spread, invisible until engaged */
    outline:       var(--border-weight-hairline) solid transparent;
    outline-offset: 0px;

    transition:
      border-color  120ms ease,
      outline-color 120ms ease,
      outline-width 120ms ease;
  }

  /* ── Engaged: promote weight via paint-only ring ───────── */
  .input:focus,
  .input:focus-visible {
    border-color:   var(--border-color-engaged);

    /* Ring takes the delta (1px) so total perceived weight = 2px */
    outline:        var(--border-weight-hairline) solid var(--border-color-engaged);
    outline-offset: 0px;
  }

  /* ── Error ─────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .input[aria-invalid="true"] {
    border-color:  var(--border-color-error);
  }

  .input[aria-invalid="true"]:focus,
  .input[aria-invalid="true"]:focus-visible {
    outline-color: var(--border-color-error);
  }

  /* ── Disabled ──────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .input:disabled {
    border-color:  var(--border-color-disabled);
    outline:       none;
  }
}
```

**Why `outline` instead of `box-shadow` for the ring:**
`outline` doesn't affect layout metrics and composites on the GPU paint layer — it is a true paint-only ring with no geometry side-effects.

### 3. Verification — visual weight at each state

| State | `border-width` | `outline` | Perceived stroke |
|---|---|---|---|
| Resting | 1px | 0 (transparent) | **1px hairline** |
| Engaged | 1px | 1px (opaque, offset 0) | **2px** |
| Error-resting | 1px | 0 (transparent) | **1px hairline** |
| Error-engaged | 1px | 1px (opaque, offset 0) | **2px** |
| Disabled | 1px | none | **1px, muted** |

---

## Principle

**Two-axis border grammar: the resting state must occupy the hairline stop on the weight axis.** The engaged state adds perceived weight via a second paint layer (outline/ring) rather than by widening the base border. This keeps the geometry stable — no layout shift, no reflow — while making the weight promotion visually unambiguous. Widening the base border directly (1px → 2px) shifts surrounding content and conflates the two axes into a single channel, which is the anti-pattern.
